stories: In recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) have demonstrated success in image recognition. Quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) are proposed as a novel extension to CNNs, utilizing quantum mechanisms. These quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient training process, reducing the input size from n to log2n. This paper compares both CNNs and QCNNs, evaluating their performance on three commonly used datasets, including MNIST hand-written digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog face images. Furthermore, data augmentation (DA), a technique commonly used to enhance CNNs' classification performance by generating similar images, is also applied to QCNNs. Notably, the results show that data augmentation failed to improve QCNNs' performance, and the underlying reasons and logic are discussed to advance our understanding of quantum machine learning theory.

In recent years, traditional convolutional neural networks have shown promise in image recognition. Quantum convolutional neural networks, a novel extension, leverage quantum principles to streamline the training process, condensing input data from n to log2n. This study compares the performance of CNNs and QCNNs on three well-known datasets, including MNIST, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog images. Data augmentation, commonly used to boost CNNs' classification accuracy by generating similar images, is also applied to QCNNs. Interestingly, data augmentation did not enhance QCNNs' performance, and the underlying explanations are examined to advance our understanding of quantum machine learning theories.
